{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QorueJPKnKGjGQdAEgkSkz","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\"\"\"Extraction workflow — for PRDs that operate on a separate target repo.\n2\t\n3\tUsed by the darkfactory extraction (PRD-500..505): the work happens in\n4\ta *different* repo on disk, so the pumice ``just test`` / ``just lint``\n5\tshell steps from the default workflow don't apply. The agent is\n6\tresponsible for whatever verification matters in the target repo.\n7\t\n8\tPredicate matches any PRD tagged ``extraction``. Priority 5 — above\n9\tdefault (0), below specialized workflows like ui-component (10).\n10\t\"\"\"\n11\t\n12\tfrom __future__ import annotations\n13\t\n14\tfrom darkfactory.workflow import AgentTask, BuiltIn, Workflow\n15\t\n16\t\n17\tdef _is_extraction(prd, prds):  # type: ignore[no-untyped-def]\n18\t    return \"extraction\" in prd.tags\n19\t\n20\t\n21\tworkflow = Workflow(\n22\t    name=\"extraction\",\n23\t    description=(\n24\t        \"Repo-extraction workflow — for PRDs whose work happens in a \"\n25\t        \"separate target repository (no pumice test/lint phase).\"\n26\t    ),\n27\t    applies_to=_is_extraction,\n28\t    priority=5,\n29\t    tasks=[\n30\t        BuiltIn(\"ensure_worktree\"),\n31\t        BuiltIn(\"set_status\", kwargs={\"to\": \"in-progress\"}),\n32\t        BuiltIn(\n33\t            \"commit\",\n34\t            kwargs={\"message\": \"chore(prd): {prd_id} start work\"},\n35\t        ),\n36\t        AgentTask(\n37\t            name=\"implement\",\n38\t            prompts=[\"prompts/role.md\", \"prompts/task.md\"],\n39\t            tools=[\n40\t                \"Read\",\n41\t                \"Edit\",\n42\t                \"Write\",\n43\t                \"Glob\",\n44\t                \"Grep\",\n45\t                # Broad bash for filesystem + git + gh against the target repo\n46\t                \"Bash\",\n47\t            ],\n48\t            model_from_capability=True,\n49\t            retries=1,\n50\t            verify_prompts=[\"prompts/verify.md\"],\n51\t        ),\n52\t        # No test/lint ShellTasks — the agent verifies in the target repo.\n53\t        BuiltIn(\n54\t            \"commit\",\n55\t            kwargs={\"message\": \"chore(prd): {prd_id} ready for review\"},\n56\t        ),\n57\t        BuiltIn(\"set_status\", kwargs={\"to\": \"review\"}),\n58\t        BuiltIn(\"lint_attribution\"),\n59\t        BuiltIn(\"push_branch\"),\n60\t        BuiltIn(\"create_pr\"),\n61\t    ],\n62\t)\n63\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d010088e-6429-4c1e-aa66-519315c26c5c","uuid":"63ad9448-87eb-4b06-9917-74f4e59e6d5a","timestamp":"2026-04-09T04:34:00.263Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/.worktrees/PRD-227.4-migrate-extraction-workflow/src/darkfactory/workflows/extraction/workflow.py","content":"\"\"\"Extraction workflow — for PRDs that operate on a separate target repo.\n\nUsed by the darkfactory extraction (PRD-500..505): the work happens in\na *different* repo on disk, so the pumice ``just test`` / ``just lint``\nshell steps from the default workflow don't apply. The agent is\nresponsible for whatever verification matters in the target repo.\n\nPredicate matches any PRD tagged ``extraction``. Priority 5 — above\ndefault (0), below specialized workflows like ui-component (10).\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom darkfactory.workflow import AgentTask, BuiltIn, Workflow\n\n\ndef _is_extraction(prd, prds):  # type: ignore[no-untyped-def]\n    return \"extraction\" in prd.tags\n\n\nworkflow = Workflow(\n    name=\"extraction\",\n    description=(\n        \"Repo-extraction workflow — for PRDs whose work happens in a \"\n        \"separate target repository (no pumice test/lint phase).\"\n    ),\n    applies_to=_is_extraction,\n    priority=5,\n    tasks=[\n        BuiltIn(\"ensure_worktree\"),\n        BuiltIn(\"set_status\", kwargs={\"to\": \"in-progress\"}),\n        BuiltIn(\n            \"commit\",\n            kwargs={\"message\": \"chore(prd): {prd_id} start work\"},\n        ),\n        AgentTask(\n            name=\"implement\",\n            prompts=[\"prompts/role.md\", \"prompts/task.md\"],\n            tools=[\n                \"Read\",\n                \"Edit\",\n                \"Write\",\n                \"Glob\",\n                \"Grep\",\n                # Broad bash for filesystem + git + gh against the target repo\n                \"Bash\",\n            ],\n            model_from_capability=True,\n            retries=1,\n            verify_prompts=[\"prompts/verify.md\"],\n        ),\n        # No test/lint ShellTasks — the agent verifies in the target repo.\n        BuiltIn(\n            \"commit\",\n            kwargs={\"message\": \"chore(prd): {prd_id} ready for review\"},\n        ),\n        BuiltIn(\"set_status\", kwargs={\"to\": \"review\"}),\n        BuiltIn(\"lint_attribution\"),\n        BuiltIn(\"push_branch\"),\n        BuiltIn(\"create_pr\"),\n    ],\n)\n","numLines":63,"startLine":1,"totalLines":63}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JSfuKzE6Pd9KkeZ9VGS9iU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to compare the extraction workflow's open/close tasks against the `PRD_IMPLEMENTATION_TEMPLATE`.\n\n**Template open:**\n1. `BuiltIn(\"ensure_worktree\")`\n2. `BuiltIn(\"set_status\", kwargs={\"to\": \"in-progress\"})`\n3. `BuiltIn(\"commit\", kwargs={\"message\": \"chore(prd): {prd_id} start work\"})`\n\n\nThe extraction workflow's opening tasks match perfectly. For the closing sequence, the template specifies summarizing the agent run, committing the transcript, setting status to review, and committing a final message—I need to verify the extraction workflow follows this same pattern. I'm seeing that the extraction workflow has structural mismatches with the template—the middle section lacks any ShellTask (which the template requires), and the close sequence differs in both ordering and task composition. Since I can't directly compose using the template, I need to handle these constraints separately.\n\nLooking at how templates work to understand whether I should create a dedicated `EXTRACTION_TEMPLATE` in `templates_builtin.py` or define one locally in the extraction workflow file.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":815,"cache_read_input_tokens":20998,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":815},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d010088e-6429-4c1e-aa66-519315c26c5c","uuid":"518c6493-54a2-4639-84fa-5c1665ce2de1"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JSfuKzE6Pd9KkeZ9VGS9iU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SY1zbwN2xZ4mvZcFgdxb2R","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/.worktrees/PRD-227.4-migrate-extraction-workflow/src/darkfactory/templates.py"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":815,"cache_read_input_tokens":20998,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":815},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d010088e-6429-4c1e-aa66-519315c26c5c","uuid":"bbdb51e4-0426-409c-99e3-97118b15ad26"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SY1zbwN2xZ4mvZcFgdxb2R","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\"\"\"Prompt file loading, variable substitution, and WorkflowTemplate abstraction.\n2\t\n3\tWhen the runner executes an :class:`~darkfactory.workflow.AgentTask`,\n4\tit needs to build the prompt the Claude Code subprocess will receive.\n5\tThat involves three steps:\n6\t\n7\t1. **Load** each file listed in ``AgentTask.prompts``, resolved\n8\t   relative to the workflow's directory.\n9\t2. **Concatenate** them with blank-line separators, preserving order.\n10\t3. **Substitute** ``{{PLACEHOLDER}}``-style tokens with values from\n11\t   the current :class:`~darkfactory.workflow.ExecutionContext`.\n12\t\n13\tThe placeholder syntax (``{{UPPERCASE_NAME}}``) is deliberately distinct\n14\tfrom Python's ``str.format`` ``{lowercase}`` style used by\n15\t``ExecutionContext.format_string`` — the two templating systems serve\n16\tdifferent purposes:\n17\t\n18\t- :meth:`ExecutionContext.format_string` is **strict**: unknown\n19\t  placeholders raise ``KeyError``. Used for commit messages and shell\n20\t  commands where typos must be caught early.\n21\t- :func:`substitute_placeholders` is **permissive**: unknown\n22\t  placeholders are left as-is. This lets agent prompts evolve\n23\t  incrementally — you can reference ``{{NEW_FIELD}}`` in a prompt\n24\t  before the context learns how to populate it, and the prompt still\n25\t  renders without exploding.\n26\t\n27\tThe split also prevents accidental collisions between Python format\n28\tstrings in Bash commands and agent-prompt placeholders.\n29\t\n30\t:class:`WorkflowTemplate` is the foundational primitive for PRD-227\n31\tworkflow templates. A template defines required opening tasks, a\n32\tconstrained middle slot, and required closing tasks. ``.compose()``\n33\tconcatenates ``[*open, *middle, *close]`` into a :class:`Workflow`,\n34\tvalidating the middle against ``middle_kinds`` and ``middle_required``\n35\tconstraints.\n36\t\"\"\"\n37\t\n38\tfrom __future__ import annotations\n39\t\n40\timport re\n41\tfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\n42\tfrom pathlib import Path\n43\tfrom typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any, Callable, Mapping\n44\t\n45\tfrom .workflow import BuiltIn, Workflow\n46\t\n47\tif TYPE_CHECKING:\n48\t    from .workflow import ExecutionContext\n49\t\n50\t\n51\tPLACEHOLDER_RE = re.compile(r\"\\{\\{(\\w+)\\}\\}\")\n52\t\"\"\"Matches ``{{NAME}}`` tokens in prompt templates.\n53\t\n54\tThe captured group is the placeholder name (alphanumeric + underscore).\n55\tNon-matching sequences pass through unchanged, so literal ``{{ }}`` in\n56\tdocumentation or code blocks inside prompts survive the substitution.\n57\t\"\"\"\n58\t\n59\t\n60\tdef load_prompt_files(workflow_dir: Path, paths: list[str]) -> str:\n61\t    \"\"\"Read and concatenate prompt files from a workflow directory.\n62\t\n63\t    Each path in ``paths`` is resolved relative to ``workflow_dir`` and\n64\t    read as UTF-8. Results are joined with ``\"\\\\n\\\\n\"`` separators so the\n65\t    agent sees them as distinct sections rather than one run-on prompt.\n66\t\n67\t    Raises ``FileNotFoundError`` with the workflow directory in the\n68\t    message if any path doesn't resolve — typos in ``AgentTask.prompts``\n69\t    should fail loudly at runtime, not silently produce empty prompts.\n70\t    \"\"\"\n71\t    parts: list[str] = []\n72\t    for path in paths:\n73\t        full = workflow_dir / path\n74\t        if not full.exists():\n75\t            raise FileNotFoundError(\n76\t                f\"prompt file not found in workflow {workflow_dir.name!r}: {path} \"\n77\t                f\"(looked in {full})\"\n78\t            )\n79\t        parts.append(full.read_text(encoding=\"utf-8\"))\n80\t    return \"\\n\\n\".join(parts)\n81\t\n82\t\n83\tdef substitute_placeholders(template: str, context: Mapping[str, object]) -> str:\n84\t    \"\"\"Replace ``{{NAME}}`` tokens in ``template`` using ``context``.\n85\t\n86\t    Unknown placeholders (names not in ``context``) are left unchanged.\n87\t    This is intentional — it lets prompt authors reference future\n88\t    placeholders without breaking the current rendering, and it means a\n89\t    ``{{CHECK_OUTPUT}}`` reference in verify.md stays literal during\n90\t    the initial rendering pass (when no check has failed yet) and gets\n91\t    substituted only on retry.\n92\t\n93\t    Values are coerced to ``str`` via ``str()``, so integers, paths,\n94\t    and dataclass reprs all work without caller ceremony.\n95\t    \"\"\"\n96\t\n97\t    def replace(match: re.Match[str]) -> str:\n98\t        key = match.group(1)\n99\t        if key in context:\n100\t            return str(context[key])\n101\t        return match.group(0)  # leave unchanged\n102\t\n103\t    return PLACEHOLDER_RE.sub(replace, template)\n104\t\n105\t\n106\tdef compose_prompt(\n107\t    workflow: Workflow,\n108\t    prompts: list[str],\n109\t    execution_context: ExecutionContext,\n110\t    extras: Mapping[str, object] | None = None,\n111\t) -> str:\n112\t    \"\"\"End-to-end: load prompt files and substitute context placeholders.\n113\t\n114\t    The standard placeholder set populated from the ExecutionContext:\n115\t\n116\t    - ``{{PRD_ID}}`` — the PRD's id\n117\t    - ``{{PRD_TITLE}}`` — the PRD's title\n118\t    - ``{{PRD_PATH}}`` — absolute path to the PRD file\n119\t    - ``{{PRD_SLUG}}`` — the slug portion of the PRD filename\n120\t    - ``{{BRANCH_NAME}}`` — the current branch name\n121\t    - ``{{BASE_REF}}`` — the base ref the branch was created from\n122\t    - ``{{WORKTREE_PATH}}`` — the worktree path (or empty string if unset)\n123\t\n124\t    ``extras`` is merged into the context after the standard keys, so\n125\t    callers can inject ad-hoc values (e.g. ``CHECK_OUTPUT`` for retry\n126\t    prompts) without modifying the ExecutionContext.\n127\t\n128\t    Raises ``ValueError`` if the workflow has no ``workflow_dir`` set\n129\t    (shouldn't happen in practice — the loader sets it — but makes the\n130\t    failure explicit if someone constructs a Workflow by hand).\n131\t    \"\"\"\n132\t    if workflow.workflow_dir is None:\n133\t        raise ValueError(\n134\t            f\"workflow {workflow.name!r} has no workflow_dir; \"\n135\t            \"the loader normally sets this at import time\"\n136\t        )\n137\t\n138\t    raw = load_prompt_files(workflow.workflow_dir, prompts)\n139\t\n140\t    prd = execution_context.prd\n141\t    context: dict[str, object] = {\n142\t        \"PRD_ID\": prd.id,\n143\t        \"PRD_TITLE\": prd.title,\n144\t        \"PRD_PATH\": str(prd.path),\n145\t        \"PRD_SLUG\": prd.slug,\n146\t        \"BRANCH_NAME\": execution_context.branch_name,\n147\t        \"BASE_REF\": execution_context.base_ref,\n148\t        \"WORKTREE_PATH\": (\n149\t            str(execution_context.worktree_path)\n150\t            if execution_context.worktree_path\n151\t            else \"\"\n152\t        ),\n153\t    }\n154\t    if extras:\n155\t        context.update(extras)\n156\t\n157\t    return substitute_placeholders(raw, context)\n158\t\n159\t\n160\t# ---------- WorkflowTemplate ----------\n161\t\n162\t\n163\tclass TemplateViolation(Exception):\n164\t    \"\"\"Raised when a composed middle violates the template's constraints.\"\"\"\n165\t\n166\t\n167\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n168\tclass WorkflowTemplate:\n169\t    \"\"\"A reusable recipe that stamps out :class:`Workflow` instances.\n170\t\n171\t    A template defines:\n172\t\n173\t    - Required **opening** tasks that always run first (``open``).\n174\t    - A constrained **middle** slot for caller-supplied tasks.\n175\t    - Required **closing** tasks that always run last (``close``).\n176\t\n177\t    :meth:`compose` validates the caller's middle tasks against\n178\t    ``middle_kinds`` and ``middle_required``, then returns a\n179\t    :class:`Workflow` whose task list is ``[*open, *middle, *close]``\n180\t    with ``template_name`` set to this template's ``name``.\n181\t    \"\"\"\n182\t\n183\t    name: str\n184\t    description: str\n185\t    open: list[BuiltIn]\n186\t    close: list[BuiltIn]\n187\t    middle_kinds: list[type] = field(default_factory=list)\n188\t    middle_required: dict[type, tuple[int, int | None]] = field(default_factory=dict)\n189\t\n190\t    def compose(\n191\t        self,\n192\t        name: str,\n193\t        description: str,\n194\t        applies_to: Callable[..., bool],\n195\t        priority: int,\n196\t        middle: list[Any],\n197\t    ) -> Workflow:\n198\t        \"\"\"Validate ``middle`` and return a complete :class:`Workflow`.\n199\t\n200\t        Parameters match :class:`Workflow` constructor arguments for the\n201\t        caller-supplied fields. ``tasks`` and ``template_name`` are set\n202\t        by this method.\n203\t\n204\t        Raises :class:`TemplateViolation` if any task in ``middle`` is\n205\t        not an instance of one of ``middle_kinds``, or if the count of\n206\t        any required kind falls outside the ``middle_required`` bounds.\n207\t        \"\"\"\n208\t        self._validate_middle(middle)\n209\t        return Workflow(\n210\t            name=name,\n211\t            description=description,\n212\t            applies_to=applies_to,\n213\t            priority=priority,\n214\t            tasks=[*self.open, *middle, *self.close],\n215\t            template_name=self.name,\n216\t        )\n217\t\n218\t    def _validate_middle(self, middle: list[Any]) -> None:\n219\t        if self.middle_kinds:\n220\t            for task in middle:\n221\t                if not isinstance(task, tuple(self.middle_kinds)):\n222\t                    raise TemplateViolation(\n223\t                        f\"Task {task!r} is not an allowed middle kind \"\n224\t                        f\"(allowed: {[k.__name__ for k in self.middle_kinds]})\"\n225\t                    )\n226\t        for kind, (min_count, max_count) in self.middle_required.items():\n227\t            actual = sum(1 for t in middle if isinstance(t, kind))\n228\t            if actual < min_count:\n229\t                raise TemplateViolation(\n230\t                    f\"Template requires at least {min_count} {kind.__name__} \"\n231\t                    f\"in the middle, got {actual}\"\n232\t                )\n233\t            if max_count is not None and actual > max_count:\n234\t                raise TemplateViolation(\n235\t                    f\"Template allows at most {max_count} {kind.__name__} \"\n236\t                    f\"in the middle, got {actual}\"\n237\t                )\n238\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d010088e-6429-4c1e-aa66-519315c26c5c","uuid":"82ca8ce2-a9f0-4dff-a44d-8c59eaf0131f","timestamp":"2026-04-09T04:34:25.058Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/.worktrees/PRD-227.4-migrate-extraction-workflow/src/darkfactory/templates.py","content":"\"\"\"Prompt file loading, variable substitution, and WorkflowTemplate abstraction.\n\nWhen the runner executes an :class:`~darkfactory.workflow.AgentTask`,\nit needs to build the prompt the Claude Code subprocess will receive.\nThat involves three steps:\n\n1. **Load** each file listed in ``AgentTask.prompts``, resolved\n   relative to the workflow's directory.\n2. **Concatenate** them with blank-line separators, preserving order.\n3. **Substitute** ``{{PLACEHOLDER}}``-style tokens with values from\n   the current :class:`~darkfactory.workflow.ExecutionContext`.\n\nThe placeholder syntax (``{{UPPERCASE_NAME}}``) is deliberately distinct\nfrom Python's ``str.format`` ``{lowercase}`` style used by\n``ExecutionContext.format_string`` — the two templating systems serve\ndifferent purposes:\n\n- :meth:`ExecutionContext.format_string` is **strict**: unknown\n  placeholders raise ``KeyError``. Used for commit messages and shell\n  commands where typos must be caught early.\n- :func:`substitute_placeholders` is **permissive**: unknown\n  placeholders are left as-is. This lets agent prompts evolve\n  incrementally — you can reference ``{{NEW_FIELD}}`` in a prompt\n  before the context learns how to populate it, and the prompt still\n  renders without exploding.\n\nThe split also prevents accidental collisions between Python format\nstrings in Bash commands and agent-prompt placeholders.\n\n:class:`WorkflowTemplate` is the foundational primitive for PRD-227\nworkflow templates. A template defines required opening tasks, a\nconstrained middle slot, and required closing tasks. ``.compose()``\nconcatenates ``[*open, *middle, *close]`` into a :class:`Workflow`,\nvalidating the middle against ``middle_kinds`` and ``middle_required``\nconstraints.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport re\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any, Callable, Mapping\n\nfrom .workflow import BuiltIn, Workflow\n\nif TYPE_CHECKING:\n    from .workflow import ExecutionContext\n\n\nPLACEHOLDER_RE = re.compile(r\"\\{\\{(\\w+)\\}\\}\")\n\"\"\"Matches ``{{NAME}}`` tokens in prompt templates.\n\nThe captured group is the placeholder name (alphanumeric + underscore).\nNon-matching sequences pass through unchanged, so literal ``{{ }}`` in\ndocumentation or code blocks inside prompts survive the substitution.\n\"\"\"\n\n\ndef load_prompt_files(workflow_dir: Path, paths: list[str]) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Read and concatenate prompt files from a workflow directory.\n\n    Each path in ``paths`` is resolved relative to ``workflow_dir`` and\n    read as UTF-8. Results are joined with ``\"\\\\n\\\\n\"`` separators so the\n    agent sees them as distinct sections rather than one run-on prompt.\n\n    Raises ``FileNotFoundError`` with the workflow directory in the\n    message if any path doesn't resolve — typos in ``AgentTask.prompts``\n    should fail loudly at runtime, not silently produce empty prompts.\n    \"\"\"\n    parts: list[str] = []\n    for path in paths:\n        full = workflow_dir / path\n        if not full.exists():\n            raise FileNotFoundError(\n                f\"prompt file not found in workflow {workflow_dir.name!r}: {path} \"\n                f\"(looked in {full})\"\n            )\n        parts.append(full.read_text(encoding=\"utf-8\"))\n    return \"\\n\\n\".join(parts)\n\n\ndef substitute_placeholders(template: str, context: Mapping[str, object]) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Replace ``{{NAME}}`` tokens in ``template`` using ``context``.\n\n    Unknown placeholders (names not in ``context``) are left unchanged.\n    This is intentional — it lets prompt authors reference future\n    placeholders without breaking the current rendering, and it means a\n    ``{{CHECK_OUTPUT}}`` reference in verify.md stays literal during\n    the initial rendering pass (when no check has failed yet) and gets\n    substituted only on retry.\n\n    Values are coerced to ``str`` via ``str()``, so integers, paths,\n    and dataclass reprs all work without caller ceremony.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def replace(match: re.Match[str]) -> str:\n        key = match.group(1)\n        if key in context:\n            return str(context[key])\n        return match.group(0)  # leave unchanged\n\n    return PLACEHOLDER_RE.sub(replace, template)\n\n\ndef compose_prompt(\n    workflow: Workflow,\n    prompts: list[str],\n    execution_context: ExecutionContext,\n    extras: Mapping[str, object] | None = None,\n) -> str:\n    \"\"\"End-to-end: load prompt files and substitute context placeholders.\n\n    The standard placeholder set populated from the ExecutionContext:\n\n    - ``{{PRD_ID}}`` — the PRD's id\n    - ``{{PRD_TITLE}}`` — the PRD's title\n    - ``{{PRD_PATH}}`` — absolute path to the PRD file\n    - ``{{PRD_SLUG}}`` — the slug portion of the PRD filename\n    - ``{{BRANCH_NAME}}`` — the current branch name\n    - ``{{BASE_REF}}`` — the base ref the branch was created from\n    - ``{{WORKTREE_PATH}}`` — the worktree path (or empty string if unset)\n\n    ``extras`` is merged into the context after the standard keys, so\n    callers can inject ad-hoc values (e.g. ``CHECK_OUTPUT`` for retry\n    prompts) without modifying the ExecutionContext.\n\n    Raises ``ValueError`` if the workflow has no ``workflow_dir`` set\n    (shouldn't happen in practice — the loader sets it — but makes the\n    failure explicit if someone constructs a Workflow by hand).\n    \"\"\"\n    if workflow.workflow_dir is None:\n        raise ValueError(\n            f\"workflow {workflow.name!r} has no workflow_dir; \"\n            \"the loader normally sets this at import time\"\n        )\n\n    raw = load_prompt_files(workflow.workflow_dir, prompts)\n\n    prd = execution_context.prd\n    context: dict[str, object] = {\n        \"PRD_ID\": prd.id,\n        \"PRD_TITLE\": prd.title,\n        \"PRD_PATH\": str(prd.path),\n        \"PRD_SLUG\": prd.slug,\n        \"BRANCH_NAME\": execution_context.branch_name,\n        \"BASE_REF\": execution_context.base_ref,\n        \"WORKTREE_PATH\": (\n            str(execution_context.worktree_path)\n            if execution_context.worktree_path\n            else \"\"\n        ),\n    }\n    if extras:\n        context.update(extras)\n\n    return substitute_placeholders(raw, context)\n\n\n# ---------- WorkflowTemplate ----------\n\n\nclass TemplateViolation(Exception):\n    \"\"\"Raised when a composed middle violates the template's constraints.\"\"\"\n\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass WorkflowTemplate:\n    \"\"\"A reusable recipe that stamps out :class:`Workflow` instances.\n\n    A template defines:\n\n    - Required **opening** tasks that always run first (``open``).\n    - A constrained **middle** slot for caller-supplied tasks.\n    - Required **closing** tasks that always run last (``close``).\n\n    :meth:`compose` validates the caller's middle tasks against\n    ``middle_kinds`` and ``middle_required``, then returns a\n    :class:`Workflow` whose task list is ``[*open, *middle, *close]``\n    with ``template_name`` set to this template's ``name``.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    name: str\n    description: str\n    open: list[BuiltIn]\n    close: list[BuiltIn]\n    middle_kinds: list[type] = field(default_factory=list)\n    middle_required: dict[type, tuple[int, int | None]] = field(default_factory=dict)\n\n    def compose(\n        self,\n        name: str,\n        description: str,\n        applies_to: Callable[..., bool],\n        priority: int,\n        middle: list[Any],\n    ) -> Workflow:\n        \"\"\"Validate ``middle`` and return a complete :class:`Workflow`.\n\n        Parameters match :class:`Workflow` constructor arguments for the\n        caller-supplied fields. ``tasks`` and ``template_name`` are set\n        by this method.\n\n        Raises :class:`TemplateViolation` if any task in ``middle`` is\n        not an instance of one of ``middle_kinds``, or if the count of\n        any required kind falls outside the ``middle_required`` bounds.\n        \"\"\"\n        self._validate_middle(middle)\n        return Workflow(\n            name=name,\n            description=description,\n            applies_to=applies_to,\n            priority=priority,\n            tasks=[*self.open, *middle, *self.close],\n            template_name=self.name,\n        )\n\n    def _validate_middle(self, middle: list[Any]) -> None:\n        if self.middle_kinds:\n            for task in middle:\n                if not isinstance(task, tuple(self.middle_kinds)):\n                    raise TemplateViolation(\n                        f\"Task {task!r} is not an allowed middle kind \"\n                        f\"(allowed: {[k.__name__ for k in self.middle_kinds]})\"\n                    )\n        for kind, (min_count, max_count) in self.middle_required.items():\n            actual = sum(1 for t in middle if isinstance(t, kind))\n            if actual < min_count:\n                raise TemplateViolation(\n                    f\"Template requires at least {min_count} {kind.__name__} \"\n                    f\"in the middle, got {actual}\"\n                )\n            if max_count is not None and actual > max_count:\n                raise TemplateViolation(\n                    f\"Template allows at most {max_count} {kind.__name__} \"\n                    f\"in the middle, got {actual}\"\n                )\n","numLines":238,"startLine":1,"totalLines":238}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01E8xAUwkNwgy64doGAJbo7C","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me compare the extraction workflow's tasks to the template:\n\n**Template open:**\n1. `BuiltIn(\"ensure_worktree\")`\n2. `BuiltIn(\"set_status\", kwargs={\"to\": \"in-progress\"})`\n3. `BuiltIn(\"commit\", kwargs={\"message\": \"chore(prd): {prd_id} start work\"})`\n\n**Extraction workflow tasks (start):**\n1. `BuiltIn(\"ensure_worktree\")` ✅\n\n\n2. `BuiltIn(\"set_status\", kwargs={\"to\": \"in-progress\"})` ✅\n3. `BuiltIn(\"commit\", kwargs={\"message\": \"chore(prd): {prd_id} start work\"})` ✅\n\nAll the opening tasks match perfectly. But looking at the middle section, the extraction workflow only has one AgentTask and no ShellTask, while the template requires at least one of each. The extraction is missing that required ShellTask.\n\nNow checking the closing sequence—the template specifies a series of built-in operations to summarize the run, commit the transcript, update status to review, commit with a review message, push the branch, and create a pull request. The extraction's end tasks include some of these same operations but they're in a different order and appear incomplete.\n\nLooking at the differences, the template starts with summarization and transcript operations that the extraction workflow skips entirely. The status update and commit happen in reverse order between the two, and the extraction includes a linting step that the template doesn't have. This means I need to create a separate extraction template that mirrors the PRD implementation's opening but has its own closing sequence—skipping the summarization steps, reordering the status and commit operations, and adding the attribution linting step. The middle section should only require agent tasks without shell task constraints.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3872,"cache_read_input_tokens":21813,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3872},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d010088e-6429-4c1e-aa66-519315c26c5c","uuid":"380398d9-c009-47e1-83d6-7ce7095d24a8"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01E8xAUwkNwgy64doGAJbo7C","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have all the info I need. The comparison:\n\n**Open tasks:** Match exactly (ensure_worktree, set_status, commit).\n\n**Close tasks:** Don't match:\n- Template: `summarize_agent_run`, `commit_transcript`, `set_status`, `commit`, `push_branch`, `create_pr`\n- Extraction: `commit`, `set_status`, `lint_attribution`, `push_branch`, `create_pr` (no summarize/transcript, different order)\n\n**Middle:** Extraction has no `ShellTask`, but template requires ≥1 `ShellTask`.\n\nI'll create an `EXTRACTION_TEMPLATE` in `templates_builtin.py` and migrate the workflow to use it."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3872,"cache_read_input_tokens":21813,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3872},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d010088e-6429-4c1e-aa66-519315c26c5c","uuid":"037c4948-8cac-44af-b6cf-3b7a42e11afa"}
